olors/labels\" — we can still add styling props.\n\nHmm, but actually the key insight is: the OUTER Box gets `width={width}`, and the inner row gets `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`. If individual Text elements are too long, they might still wrap internally. But if we also constrain the inner Box width and use `overflow=\"hidden\"`, that should clip.\n\nLet me think about what's cleanest. The instructions say: \"the inner content row(s) should clip rather than reflow into extra lines — prefer giving the row(s) `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and/or threading the width down.\"\n\nSo the approach:\n- Outer Box: `width={width}` (when provided), `borderStyle=\"single\"`\n- Inner chip row: `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, and maybe `overflow=\"hidden\"`\n- Second row: same treatment\n\nActually, with a border, the inner content width is `width - 2` (border takes 1 char each side). If we set the inner Box to also have `width={width - 2}` or just let it inherit, and `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, chips that don't fit will overflow but not wrap.\n\nBut will Ink clip the overflow? In Ink, overflow isn't visually clipped by default — it might still render. Hmm. But the key point is line count stability. Even if text overflows horizontally, it shouldn't create extra lines if `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` is set and individual Text elements don't wrap.\n\nFor individual Text elements, we might need to ensure they don't wrap. In Ink 5, `<Text>` wraps by default when it hits the container width. To prevent wrapping, we can... actually I'm not sure Ink has a `nowrap` for Text. Let me think.\n\nIn Ink, text wrapping happens when the text is wider than the available space. The `Text` component doesn't have a `wrap` prop in older versions, but Ink 5 might. Actually, looking at Ink's docs, there isn't a direct `nowrap` prop for Text. But if the parent Box has `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and the Text has a fixed/limited width, it might truncate.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that guarantees line-count stability: give each chip row `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and also set `overflow=\"hidden\"` on the row Box. In Ink, `overflow=\"hidden\"` should clip content that exceeds the box dimensions.\n\nWait, does Ink support `overflow`? Let me think... Yoga supports `overflow` property. Ink's Box does pass `overflow` to Yoga. So `overflow=\"hidden\"` should work to clip.\n\nBut even without clipping, the important thing is that the LINE COUNT doesn't grow. If `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` prevents items from moving to new lines, and individual Text elements... hmm, if a Text element is wider than its flex container, what happens? In Yoga, the Text element would have a measured width larger than the container, but with `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, it stays on the same line. The text itself might still wrap internally if Ink measures it as wrapping.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is more subtle. Let me reconsider.\n\nIn Ink, when a `<Text>` is rendered, its measurement depends on the available width. If the available width is small, Ink wraps the text to multiple lines, increasing the measured height. This is the core issue — not just flex wrapping of sibling elements, but text wrapping within individual Text elements.\n\nSo to truly prevent line-count growth, we need to prevent text wrapping within individual Text elements. \n\nIn Ink 5, I believe you can use `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">` or `<Text wrap=\"truncate-end\">` to prevent wrapping and truncate instead. Let me check... Actually, Ink 5's `Text` component does have a `wrap` prop with options: `'wrap'` (default) and `'truncate'`, `'truncate-start'`, `'truncate-middle'`, `'truncate-end'`.\n\nWait, I'm not 100% sure about this. Let me think about what's available. In Ink 3+, there's `truncate` prop on Text. In Ink 5, I believe the API is `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">`.\n\nHmm, actually looking at Ink's source, the `Text` component in Ink 5 supports:\n- No wrap prop → wraps by default\n- `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">` → truncates with ellipsis\n\nBut I'm not certain. Let me take a different approach.\n\nActually, the simplest and most robust approach: set `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` on the chip row Box AND set `overflow=\"hidden\"` on it. This way, even if individual Text elements try to wrap, the Box clips them. But does `overflow=\"hidden\"` actually prevent the Text from measuring as multi-line? Probably not — Yoga measures the Text's intrinsic size first, then overflow clips the visual output but the layout height might still be tall.\n\nOK, let me think about this more carefully. The real fix needs to ensure that when width shrinks, the rendered output (as measured by `output.split('\\n').length`) doesn't grow.\n\nThe most reliable way: use `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` on the row, and for each Text element, prevent wrapping. If Ink 5 Text supports `wrap=\"truncate\"`, that's ideal. Let me assume it does based on Ink 5 docs.\n\nActually, I just recalled: Ink 5's `Text` component does NOT have a `wrap` prop. The wrapping behavior is controlled by the Yoga layout. However, there IS a `truncate` prop in some versions.\n\nLet me look at this from a different angle. The instructions say:\n\n\"prefer giving the row(s) `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and/or threading the width down\"\n\nAnd: \"The non-negotiable property: for a fixed `status`, StatusLine's rendered line count must be STABLE / monotonic across width changes — it must not grow extra lines when width shrinks.\"\n\nSo maybe `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` alone is sufficient? If the chip row has `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, the chips stay on one line. Individual Text elements might still wrap internally, but if each chip is short enough (like \"gpt-x\", \"200 tok\", etc.), they might not wrap even at small widths.\n\nBut the test uses \"a `status` whose chips' combined length far EXCEEDS that width (e.g. a long `model`/`cwd`)\". So individual chips could be long (like a long cwd path). At width 20, a long cwd would wrap within its Text element.\n\nHmm. Let me think about what Ink actually does. In Ink, when a `<Tex