chips don't wrap. So wideLines = 4. And narrowLines with fix = 4. 4 ≤ 4, passes. Without fix, narrowLines = 5+, 5 > 4, fails. \n\nLet me also add the hard bound: `expect(narrowLines).toBeLessThanOrEqual(5)`. With fix, 4 ≤ 5, passes. Without fix, 5+ might be 5, which passes. Hmm, that's not great. Let me use `toBeLessThanOrEqual(4)` instead. With fix, 4 ≤ 4, passes. Without fix, 5 > 4, fails. But what if the StatusLine has 5 lines normally (e.g., with padding)? Then even with the fix, 5 ≤ 4 fails. BAD.\n\nI don't know the exact line count. Let me just use the `narrowLines <= wideLines` assertion, which is robust regardless of the exact count. And add a comment about the expected count.\n\nActually, let me also add: `expect(narrowLines).toEqual(wideLines)`. This is stronger — not just ≤ but exactly equal. With fix, both are 4 (or whatever), equal. Without fix, narrow > wide, not equal. This is better.\n\nBut what if at width=10, some border rendering differs from width=80? Like, the border might have different line counts? No, the border is always 1 line top + 1 line bottom, regardless of width. So the line count should be the same.\n\nOK, let me use `toEqual`:\n\n```tsx\nexpect(narrowLines).toEqual(wideLines);\n```\n\nThis is the strongest assertion: line count is exactly the same at narrow and wide widths. Without fix, they differ (narrow > wide). With fix, they're equal.\n\nLet me finalize the test:\n\n```tsx\nit('line count stays stable when width is narrow (no wrap-driven growth)', () => {\n  const status = selectStatusLine(baseState, {\n    model: 'gpt-x',\n    cwd: '/work',\n    maxContext: 200,\n  });\n\n  const narrow = render(<StatusLine status={status} width={10} />).lastFrame() ?? '';\n  const wide = render(<StatusLine status={status} width={80} />).lastFrame() ?? '';\n\n  expect(narrow.split('\\n').length).toEqual(wide.split('\\n').length);\n});\n```\n\nSimple and clear. The non-tautological argument: without `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` on the inner rows, the `width={10}` constraint causes chips to wrap to multiple lines, making `narrow` have more lines than `wide`. With `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, chips don't wrap, and both have the same line count.\n\nWait, but I need to also make sure the test FAILS when the fix is reverted. If the fix is reverted:\n- `width` prop doesn't exist → TypeScript error → `tsc --noEmit` fails → gate fails\n- This counts as a failure\n\nBut the instructions say the test should fail at runtime (\"chips wrap → more lines\"). If TypeScript fails, the test doesn't even run. Is that acceptable?\n\nI think in the context of the gate (`tsc --noEmit && npx vitest run`), a TypeScript failure prevents vitest from running, so the test \"fails\" in the sense that the gate doesn't pass. But the instructions specifically say \"The test MUST FAIL against the current code (no width prop → chips wrap → more lines).\"\n\nHmm, maybe I should write the test to also work without the `width` prop. Like, test both with and without width:\n\nActually no, the test should use the `width` prop because that's part of the fix. The test is written for the fixed code. If you revert the fix, the test fails (either TypeScript error or runtime failure if you keep the prop but remove flexWrap).\n\nI think the non-tautological argument is solid: \"If you keep the `width` prop but remove `flexWrap='nowrap'` from the inner rows, the width constraint causes chips to wrap, and `narrow.split('\\n').length` exceeds `wide.split('\\n').length`, making the test fail. This proves the test is not tautological — it specifically validates the `flexWrap='nowrap'` behavior, not just the presence of the `width` prop.\"\n\nOK, I'm going with this. Let me write the final answer now.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the case where `width` is `undefined` in the component. When `width` is `undefined`, `width={undefined}` is passed to the Box. In Ink/Yoga, `undefined` width means \"auto\" — the Box sizes to content. This is the same as not passing `width` at all. So existing tests that don't pass `width` will still work. Good.\n\nFor `overflow=\"hidden\"`: this is always applied. When `width` is not set (auto), the Box sizes to content, and `overflow=\"hidden\"` doesn't clip anything (content fits exactly). So it's safe for existing tests.\n\nFor `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`: this is always applied on inner rows. When `width` is not set (auto), the Box sizes to content, and `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` doesn't change anything (all children fit on one line because the Box is content-sized). So it's safe for existing tests.\n\nWait, actually, is that true? If the outer Box is auto-sized (no width), and the inner row has `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, the inner row would try to fit all chips on one line. The inner row's width would be the sum of all chips + gaps. The outer Box would then size to this width (plus borders). So the StatusLine would be as wide as its content, potentially wider than the terminal.\n\nIn existing tests (no width prop), this might change behavior. Previously, the inner row might have wrapped (if the default terminal width was 80 and chips exceeded 80). With `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, chips don't wrap, and the StatusLine is wider.\n\nBut in ink-testing-library, the default `columns` is 80. If the StatusLine's content is < 80 chars, no change. If > 80 chars, the StatusLine would now be wider than 80, which might cause issues.\n\nHmm, but the existing test uses `model: 'gpt-x', cwd: '/work'` which are short. The combined chips are probably < 80 chars. So no change. Good.\n\nBut to be safe, maybe I should only apply `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` when `width` is provided? Like:\n\n```tsx\n<Box gap={1} {...(width !== undefined ? { flexWrap: \"nowrap\", overflow: \"hidden\" } : {})}>\n```\n\nThis is uglier but safer. It only constrains wrapping when `width` is provided, preserving existing behavior when `width` is not provided.\n\nActually, the instructions say: \"Apply it to the outer `<Box>` as `width={width}` (only when provided — keep it optional so existing isolated tests that render `<StatusLine status={...} />` with no width still pass and don't crash).\"\n\nThis suggests the `width` application should be conditional. But for `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, the instructions say \"the inner content row(s) should clip rather than reflow into extra lines — prefer giving the row(s) `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and/or threading the width down.\"\n\nI think applying `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` unconditionally is fine, as long as existing tests pass. The existing test uses short chips that fit in 80 cols, so `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` doesn't change anything.\n\nBut to be extra safe, let me apply `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` conditionally too:\n\n```tsx\n<Box gap={1} flexWrap={width !== undefined ? \"nowrap\" : \"wrap\"}>\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting ugly. Let me just apply it unconditionally and trust that existing tests pass. The existing test checks `expect(frame).toContain('gpt-x')` — this would still pass regardless of flexWrap behavior.\n\nOK, I'll apply `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and `overflow=\"hidden\"` unconditionally on inner rows, and `width={width}` and `overflow=\"hidden\"` on the outer Box. This is clean and should work.\n\nLet me write the final answer now. For real.\n\nActually, I want to also think about whether `overflow=\"hidden\"` on the outer Box might cause issues with the border. In Ink, the border is drawn as part of the Box's rendering. `overflow=\"hidden\"` clips children, not the Box's own border. So the border should still render correctly. Good.\n\nOne more thing: the instructions mention \"the non-negotiable property: for a fixed `status`, StatusLine's rendered line count must be STABLE / monotonic across width changes — it must not grow extra lines when width shrinks.\"\n\nMy fix ensures this:\n1. `width={width}` constrains the outer Box to the given width\n2. `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` on inner rows prevents chips from wrapping to new lines\n3. `overflow=\"hidden\"` clips any horizontal overflow, preventing terminal-level wrapping\n\nThe line count is determined by the fixed structure (2 content rows + 2 border lines = 4 lines), regardless of width. ✓\n\nOK, writing the answer now.\n\nLet me think about the format. I need:\n1. For each changed/new file: path, full content of changed region, one-line rationale\n2. Short \"why the test is non-tautological\" note\n\nLet me draft:\n\n---\n\n## `src/ui/StatusLine.tsx`\n\n**Rationale:** Add optional `width` prop and constrain inner rows with `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` + `overflow=\"hidden\"` so line count is width-stable.\n\n**Changes:**\n\n1. Props interface — add `width?: number`:\n\n```tsx\nexport interface StatusLineProps {\n  status: StatusLineState;\n  width?: number;\n}\n```\n\n2. Component signature — destructure `width`:\n\n```tsx\nexport function StatusLine({ status, width }: StatusLineProps) {\n```\n\n3. Outer Box — add `width={width}` and `overflow=\"hidden\"` to the existing props:\n\n```tsx\n// Before:\n<Box flexDirection=\"column\" borderStyle=\"single\" ...>\n// After:\n<Box flexDirection=\"column\" borderStyle=\"single\" width={width} overflow=\"hidden\" ...>\n```\n\n4. Inner chip row — add `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and `overflow=\"hidden\"`:\n\n```tsx\n// Before:\n<Box gap={1} ...>\n// After:\n<Box gap={1} flexWrap=\"nowrap\" overflow=\"hidden\" ...>\n```\n\n5. Second content row — add `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and `overflow=\"hidden\"`:\n\n```tsx\n// Before:\n<Box ...>\n// After:\n<Box flexWrap=\"nowrap\" overflow=\"hidden\" ...>\n```\n\n---\n\nHmm, this is still imprecise because I don't know the exact existing code. Let me try to be more explicit by showing the full returned JSX with the changes applied. But I don't know the exact chips.\n\nOK, I think the best I can do is describe the changes clearly with before/after patterns. The synthesizer should be able to figure out the exact code. Let me write it up.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the approach. Instead of trying to describe changes to unknown code, let me present the changes as precise search-and-replace instructions. This is common in patch descriptions.\n\nLet me write the final answer now. I'll be concise but precise.","reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"Let me analyze the bug and plan the fix.\n\nThe issue is that `StatusLine` doesn't have an explicit width, so when the terminal shrinks, chips wrap to more lines, and Ink's redraw logic doesn't erase enough lines, leaving residue.\n\nThe fix:\n1. Add `width?: number` prop to `StatusLine`, apply it to the outer Box, and ensure inner rows don't wrap (use `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` or similar).\n2. Thread `columns` from `app.tsx`.\n3. Optionally debounce `useTerminalSize`.\n\nLet me think about the StatusLine implementation. I need to see the current code. Since I don't have the actual file contents, I need to infer from the description and produce a patch.\n\nWait, I need to produce the full new content of changed regions. But I don't have the actual current file contents. Let me think about what I know:\n\n- `StatusLine.tsx` renders a `<Box flexDirection=\"column\" borderStyle=\"single\" ...>` with a row of gap'd `<Text>` chips and a second row.\n- `app.tsx` line ~319 has `<StatusLine status={status} />`\n- `useTerminalSize.ts` returns `{ columns, rows }`\n\nI need to be careful here. Since I don't have the exact current file contents, I should describe the changes precisely enough. But the instructions say \"full new content of each changed region (clear enough that a synthesizer can apply it verbatim).\"\n\nLet me think about what the StatusLine component likely looks like and produce a reasonable patch. Actually, I should focus on the specific changes needed and describe them clearly.\n\nLet me think about the key changes:\n\n### StatusLine.tsx\n\nCurrent (inferred):\n```tsx\nimport React from 'react';\nimport { Box, Text } from 'ink';\n\nexport interface StatusLineProps {\n  status: StatusLineState;\n}\n\nexport function StatusLine({ status }: StatusLineProps) {\n  // ... renders chips\n  return (\n    <Box flexDirection=\"column\" borderStyle=\"single\" ...>\n      <Box gap={1}>\n        <Text>...</Text>\n        ...\n      </Box>\n      <Box>...</Box>\n    </Box>\n  );\n}\n```\n\nI need to:\n1. Add `width?: number` to props\n2. Apply `width={width}` to outer Box (conditionally)\n3. Add `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` to inner rows so chips don't wrap\n\nActually, with `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, if chips exceed width, they'll overflow/clip rather than wrap. That's what we want — stable line count.\n\nBut wait, in Ink, `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` means items won't wrap to new lines. They'll be clipped or overflow. That's the desired behavior for line-count stability.\n\nLet me think about the test. The test should:\n- Render `<StatusLine status={status} width={20} />` with long chips\n- Assert line count is bounded (e.g., ≤ 4)\n- This fails without the width prop / flexWrap because chips wrap to many lines\n\nActually, the test needs to FAIL against current code. Current code doesn't have a `width` prop at all. So if I write `<StatusLine status={status} width={20} />`, the current code would have a TypeScript error (unknown prop). Hmm.\n\nWait, the test should fail against current code meaning the behavior would be wrong. But if the prop doesn't exist in current code, the test wouldn't even compile. Let me re-read...\n\n\"The test MUST FAIL against the current code (no width prop → chips wrap → more lines) and PASS after the fix.\"\n\nI think the intent is: if you reverted the StatusLine fix (removed width prop and flexWrap), the test would fail. But if the prop doesn't exist, it's a compile error, not a test failure. \n\nHmm, maybe the test should render without width and check line count? No, the test should use width to demonstrate stability.\n\nActually, I think the point is: the test uses `width={20}`. With the fix, the line count is bounded. Without the fix (if you revert), either it doesn't compile (which is a \"failure\") or if you just remove the flexWrap but keep the optional prop, the chips wrap and line count exceeds the bound.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The non-tautological argument: Without `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and `width` constraint, Ink's flex layout wraps chips to multiple lines when content exceeds width. With the fix, `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` prevents wrapping, so line count stays constant regardless of content length vs width. The test renders with a tiny width (20) and very long chip content, then asserts line count ≤ some small number. Without the fix, the chips would wrap and produce many more lines.\n\nBut actually, does `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` in Ink actually prevent wrapping? Let me think... In Ink, `Box` uses Yoga layout. `flexWrap` controls whether children wrap. With `nowrap`, children stay on one line and may overflow. Yes, that should work.\n\nHowever, there's a subtlety: even with `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, if individual `<Text>` elements are longer than the available width, Ink might still wrap the text within each Text element. To prevent that, we might need `textWrap=\"truncate\"` or similar on the Text elements, or set `overflow=\"hidden\"`.\n\nActually in Ink, `<Text>` has a `wrap` prop. By default, text wraps. We might need to set the Text elements to not wrap. But the instructions say \"do not change the visible chip set or their colors/labels\" — we can still add styling props.\n\nHmm, but actually the key insight is: the OUTER Box gets `width={width}`, and the inner row gets `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`. If individual Text elements are too long, they might still wrap internally. But if we also constrain the inner Box width and use `overflow=\"hidden\"`, that should clip.\n\nLet me think about what's cleanest. The instructions say: \"the inner content row(s) should clip rather than reflow into extra lines — prefer giving the row(s) `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and/or threading the width down.\"\n\nSo the approach:\n- Outer Box: `width={width}` (when provided), `borderStyle=\"single\"`\n- Inner chip row: `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, and maybe `overflow=\"hidden\"`\n- Second row: same treatment\n\nActually, with a border, the inner content width is `width - 2` (border takes 1 char each side). If we set the inner Box to also have `width={width - 2}` or just let it inherit, and `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, chips that don't fit will overflow but not wrap.\n\nBut will Ink clip the overflow? In Ink, overflow isn't visually clipped by default — it might still render. Hmm. But the key point is line count stability. Even if text overflows horizontally, it shouldn't create extra lines if `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` is set and individual Text elements don't wrap.\n\nFor individual Text elements, we might need to ensure they don't wrap. In Ink 5, `<Text>` wraps by default when it hits the container width. To prevent wrapping, we can... actually I'm not sure Ink has a `nowrap` for Text. Let me think.\n\nIn Ink, text wrapping happens when the text is wider than the available space. The `Text` component doesn't have a `wrap` prop in older versions, but Ink 5 might. Actually, looking at Ink's docs, there isn't a direct `nowrap` prop for Text. But if the parent Box has `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and the Text has a fixed/limited width, it might truncate.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that guarantees line-count stability: give each chip row `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` and also set `overflow=\"hidden\"` on the row Box. In Ink, `overflow=\"hidden\"` should clip content that exceeds the box dimensions.\n\nWait, does Ink support `overflow`? Let me think... Yoga supports `overflow` property. Ink's Box does pass `overflow` to Yoga. So `overflow=\"hidden\"` should work to clip.\n\nBut even without clipping, the important thing is that the LINE COUNT doesn't grow. If `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` prevents items from moving to new lines, and individual Text elements... hmm, if a Text element is wider than its flex container, what happens? In Yoga, the Text element would have a measured width larger than the container, but with `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"`, it stays on the same line. The text itself might still wrap internally if Ink measures it as wrapping.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is more subtle. Let me reconsider.\n\nIn Ink, when a `<Text>` is rendered, its measurement depends on the available width. If the available width is small, Ink wraps the text to multiple lines, increasing the measured height. This is the core issue — not just flex wrapping of sibling elements, but text wrapping within individual Text elements.\n\nSo to truly prevent line-count growth, we need to prevent text wrapping within individual Text elements. \n\nIn Ink 5, I believe you can use `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">` or `<Text wrap=\"truncate-end\">` to prevent wrapping and truncate instead. Let me check... Actually, Ink 5's `Text` component does have a `wrap` prop with options: `'wrap'` (default) and `'truncate'`, `'truncate-start'`, `'truncate-middle'`, `'truncate-end'`.\n\nWait, I'm not 100% sure about this. Let me think about what's available. In Ink 3+, there's `truncate` prop on Text. In Ink 5, I believe the API is `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">`.\n\nHmm, actually looking at Ink's source, the `Text` component in Ink 5 supports:\n- No wrap prop → wraps by default\n- `<Text wrap=\"truncate\">` → truncates with ellipsis\n\nBut I'm not certain. Let me take a different approach.\n\nActually, the simplest and most robust approach: set `flexWrap=\"nowrap\"` on the chip row Box AND set `overflow=\"hidden\"` on it. This way, even if individual Text elements try to wrap, the Box clips them. But does `overflow=\"hidden\"` actually prevent the Text from measuring as multi-line? Probably not — Yoga measures the Text's intrinsic size first, then overflow clips the visual output but the layout height might still be tall.\n\nOK, let me think about this more carefully. The real fix needs to ensure that when width shrinks, the rendered output (as measured by `out